The article discusses an upcoming event to commemorate the 30th anniversary of the Family and Medical Leave Act (FMLA). President Biden will host the event, joined by Vice President Harris, members of his Cabinet, and former President Bill Clinton, who signed the FMLA into law. The FMLA allows workers to take up to 12 weeks of unpaid leave to care for a new child, a sick family member, or themselves without the risk of losing their jobs or health insurance. The President will reaffirm his commitment to passing a national paid family and medical leave program. The article also mentions recent actions taken by the administration to support women in the workplace, such as the passage of the Pregnant Workers Fairness Act and the PUMP Act for Nursing Mothers. Additionally, the President will issue a presidential memorandum to ensure the federal government is a model employer by allowing employees time away from work to care for themselves and their loved ones. The article emphasizes the importance of the care economy in driving economic growth and highlights the need for policies to support workers with care responsibilities. It concludes by addressing questions about the inclusion of paid leave in the President's budget proposal and potential executive actions to address these issues.